         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">18/10/91. ¶  ¶ Let me offer, venerable and illustrious friend, my best felicitation to the bestowal of the order "Pour le Mérite", and I rejoice that thus the highest scientific distinction in Prussia...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">91.10.18</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To Alphonse de Candolle</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">Bibliothèque des Conservatoire et Jardin botaniques, Geneva.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">18/10/91.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Let me offer, venerable and illustrious friend, my best felicitation to the bestowal of the order "Pour le Mérite", and I rejoice that thus the highest scientific distinction in Prussia has been conferred on you as so worthy a recipient! It is also very gratifying, that you keep mentally so fresh, and I trust that you neither suffer from bodily ailing. As said before, I wish you will attain a Chevreulian age!<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The French chemist Michel-Eugène Chevreul died aged 102 in 1889.</p>
               </note> Of the "<name key="Acacia">Acacia</name>s"<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     </seg>The first decade was issued by March 1887 (B87.13.04), and the thirteenth, the last, was ready for distribution in August 1888 (B88.13.01).</p>
               </note> not more than 13 Decades appeared hitherto, because of 70 species, <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">nowhere</hi>
               </seg> hitherto figured, I have not yet either the flowers or the fruits, and I have never illustrated pictorially a plant unless I could give the analysis from the <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">flower-bud to the embryo</hi>
               </seg>. The expedition, sent on my suggestion by Sir Th Elder through the one yet unknown great Austral. Desert will likely bring more material of <name key="Eremophila">Eremophila</name> and <name key="Myoporum">Myoporum</name>. The Explorers have just arrived in W.A. not finding any water for <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">34</hi>
               </seg> successive days!<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     </seg>See the telegram sent by the leader of the Elder Exploring Expedition, David Lindsay, to the SA Branch of the Royal Geographical Society, <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Age</seg>, 15 October 1891, p. 6.</p>
               </note> There is only one similar occurrence, Gerhard Rolfs in the Lybian Desert. Let me express my best thanks for sending me the highly important volume on <name key="Melastomaceae">Melastomaceae</name> by the excellent Cogniaux.<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Cogniaux (1891).</p>
               </note> If only all other orders under your and M. Casimir D.C.<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Casimir de Candolle.</p>
               </note> auspices could be brought out in a similar almost exhaustive manner. The issue of the lithographic illustrations requires here much vigilance on my part. The delineator just made a drawing of <name key="Salsola%20Kali">Salsola Kali</name> with a <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">hemicyclic</hi>
               </seg> embryo.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">With regardful remembrance your</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd von Mueller.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Acacia">Acacia</name>
            </p>
